{{infobox person |name=Juan José de Jesús Yas |image=Manueldejesusyas.jpg |caption=Yas in the 1890s. |birth_date=1846 |death_date=1917 |birth_place=[[Fujisawa, Iwate]], {{JAP}} |death_place=[[Antigua Guatemala]], {{GUA}} |occupation=Photographer and translator }}
'''Juan José de Jesús Yas''' (1856 - 1917) was a Japanese photographer who established himself in [[Antigua Guatemala]], [[Guatemala]] and documented that city toward the end of the 19th century and early 20th century.
==Biography== [[File:Manueldejesusyas3.jpg|200px|thumb|Yas and his wife on their wedding day.]]
Yas arrived to Guatemala as translator of the famous Mexican astronomer Covarrubias and he liked photography so much, that he became a student of German professor Herbruger.<ref name=fotofest>{{cite web|url=http://www.fotofest.org/exhibitions/faces-of-history/yas.htm |title=Yas |date=2012 |accessdate=22 August 2015 |website=Fotofest |ref=harv |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120515220748/http://www.fotofest.org/exhibitions/faces-of-history/yas.htm |archivedate=May 15, 2012 }}</ref>
==Death==
Died in Antigua Guatemala in 1917.
