'''Nils Ivar Agøy''' (born 19 November 1959) is a Norwegian historian, theologian, [[Tolkien research|tolkienologist]] and translator.

He hails from [[Gjøvik]].<ref name=50y>{{cite news|title=Jubilanter|date=19 November 2009|work=Aftenposten|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He took the [[cand.philol.]] degree in history at the [[University of Oslo]] in 1987, with the master's thesis ''Kampen mot vernetvangen. Militærnekterspørsmålet i Norge 1885–1922''. The thesis chronicled and explained [[conscientious objection]] in Norway before <!--it was legalized under certain circumstances in-->1922. His academic advisor was Jorunn Bjørgum.

Already in 1988 he graduated with the [[cand.theol.]] degree in theology at the [[MF Norwegian School of Theology]]. Subsequently, he was employed as a [[research fellow]] in history at the [[Peace Research Institute Oslo]],<ref name=50y/> finishing his [[dr.philos.]] degree in history in 1994. His thesis ''Militæretaten og "den indre fiende" fra 1905 til 1940. Hemmelige sikkerhetsstyrker i Norge sett i et skandinavisk perspektiv'' explored the military precautions against "inner enemies"—defined as revolutionary segments—between the [[Dissolution of the union between Norway and Sweden|1905 Norwegian independence]] and the Second World War, against a Scandinavian backdrop. His doctoral advisor was [[Ottar Dahl]].

He was appointed as [[associate professor]] of modern history at [[Telemark University College]] in 1994, and was promoted to professor in 2002.<ref name=50y/> In 2010 he released ''Kirken og arbeiderbevegelsen'', the result of ten years of work. The book explores ties between the [[Church of Norway]] and other congregations, and the labour movement in Norway. He concluded that the relations between Christians and labour leaders were less marked by strife and more by cooperation that hitherto believed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fiendar med sams kamp|date=22 December 2010|pages=26–27|author=Kulås, Guri|work=Klassekampen|language=Norwegian}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Fiendskap og fellesskap|date=22 January 2011|pages=56–57|author=Ravn, Lars|work=Telemarksavisa|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

Agøy is a co-founder of Norwegian Tolkien Society Arthedain.

Agøy's translation debut was [[J. R. R. Tolkien]]'s ''[[Silmarillion]]''. For this he was awarded the [[Bastian Prize]], a translator's prize in Norway, in 1995.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bastianprisen til Moren Vesaas|date=5 October 1995|agency=Norwegian News Agency|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He has later been a jury member for the children's literature class of the Bastian Prize, which is awarded by the [[Norwegian Association of Literary Translators]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ble satt pris på|date=3 October 2003|work=Klassekampen|language=Norwegian}}</ref> In 1997 he released the second Norwegian translation of ''[[The Hobbit]]'',<ref>{{cite news|title=– Vår tids største eventyrforteller|date=20 December 2001|page=|author=Wærhaug, Sølvi|work=VG|language=Norwegian}}</ref> and he has also translated ''[[Unfinished Tales|Unfinished Tales of Númenor and Middle-earth]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Norsk bok om Tolkiens verden|date=5 November 2003|page=40|author=Hanssen, Kurt|work=Dagbladet|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

In 2003 he released a book on J. R. R. Tolkien himself, titled ''Mytenes mann'' ("Man of the Myths"). The purpose was to write an introductory Tolkien book in Norwegian, and Agøy used original Tolkien documents archived in [[Oxford]] to construct a compounded biography and analysis of Tolkien's body of work.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nordmann med bok om den ukjente Tolkien|date=15 December 2003|page=47|author=Wærhaug, Sølvi|work=VG|language=Norwegian}}</ref> The book received a favourable review in ''[[Verdens Gang|VG]]''; the reviewer gave a [[dice throw (review)|dice throw]] of 5 out of 6 and complimented Agøy for his "deep insight in Tolkien's world of ideas and sources of inspiration".<ref>{{cite news|title=Atter en Tolkien-bok|date=15 December 2003|page=47|author=Rydne, Jon H|work=VG|language=Norwegian}}</ref> ''[[Aftenposten]]'' praised it moderately as a "readable entry portal to the world of Tolkien".<ref>{{cite news|title=Tar massekulturen på alvor|date=17 December 2003|page=|author=Lund, Ingrid K|work=Aftenposten|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

He resides in [[Bø i Telemark]], where Telemark University College is located, and is married to current secretary-general and former chair of the [[Church of Norway Council on Ecumenical and International Relations]], [[Berit Hagen Agøy]].

